Strong priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the aftershocks of the COVID-19.
However, the most "fragile" countries in the world are facing a set of particularly complex issues.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already struggling with poverty, conflict, corruption, and poor public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to deal with the COVID-19 crisis.
Ce dont chaque pays a besoin afin de traverser la pandémie est précisément ce qu’il manque aux États fragiles : un appareil d’État en mesure d’élaborer et de mettre en œuvre un plan d’action, un corps de police efficace pour faire appliquer les règles, des programmes sociaux qui fournissent des fonds, de l’approvisionnement ainsi que des services de santé pour soigner les personnes infectées.
The lack of state capacity is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also passes through trust in the intervention of the State.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not benefit from much public support.
In countries recovering from conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will refrain from supporting the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an indispensable component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the formal economy is not strong enough to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of youth and geographic remoteness.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, we must acknowledge that this was not the case.
In the past few weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were initially hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. These will not only be the result of national lockdowns, but also of what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from expatriates have dropped, prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for most of their food supply, there is increasing talk of "hunger" and even "famine."
We should now have understood that the problems of less developed countries are becoming for the most part global problems, whether in the form of mass migration, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the destitute population will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will not cease to worsen.
That is why the Council on State Fragility has set as its absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must overcome.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, as well as heads of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim will be to guide national and international political decision-makers on how fragile states will emerge from this crisis and how they will tackle their broader and deeper problems.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the wise use of data will be essential.
For example, it has been widely proven that targeted containment of local outbreaks is often more appropriate than nationwide lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
Nevertheless, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency dissipates.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection should be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telephone networks should be used to gather information on immediate needs and to make regular small payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which grew rice, has become increasingly dependent over the last few decades.
In a more general sense, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Initiatives for local production of basic crops must be rapidly deployed on a much broader scale.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved international development institutions; small businesses in less developed countries are often neglected and suffer the adverse consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve an objective by investing in large-scale projects in bigger economies).
Nevertheless, it is precisely these small businesses that need more significant investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid must repay approximately 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
In order to prevent this financial shock, we call on all G20 members to temporarily suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Furthermore, it is crucial that all fragile states obtain emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions — particularly countries that do not usually have access to financing from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community acts swiftly, we can mitigate the worst repercussions of the pandemic.
If there is indeed a lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we act faster than the virus.
